    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Keep the Mideast Talks Alive</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Moshe Katz letter asks why Palestinians continue to throw rocks if they are being killed, and how there can be peace with people who do not value their own lives</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mideast Crisis Management'' (editorial, Oct. 18):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mideast Crisis Management'' (editorial, Oct. 18):</p>
        <p>You believe that if Yasir Arafat and Prime Minister Ehud Barak ''make public statements urging an immediate end'' to the recent violence, ''it may be possible to start repairing the immense damage inflicted on the peace process.''</p>
        <p>Yet what if the ''peace process,'' from a Palestinian perspective, has always been damaged goods, and its failure to satisfy any reasonable definition of Palestinian justice itself an incitement to violent resistance?</p>
        <p>Even the most successful implementation of the current peace process would consign those now living under occupation to a quasi-nation segregated from itself and its neighbors by settlements and Israeli border control.</p>
        <p>ANTONIO LOPEZ  Houston, Oct. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
